

1
00:00:00,550 --> 00:00:03,410
<v ->The TCP/IP model.</v>
2
00:00:03.410 --> 00:00:05.570 line:15% 
Now, if you remember all the way back
3
00:00:05.570 --> 00:00:07.490 line:15% 
when we did the OSI model overview,
4
00:00:07.490 --> 00:00:10.550 line:15% 
I mentioned that the OSI model was a reference model.
5
00:00:10.550 --> 00:00:13.270 line:15% 
But it wasn't the only reference model out there.
6
00:00:13.270 --> 00:00:15.270 line:15% 
The other big one that we're going to talk about here
7
00:00:15.270 --> 00:00:18.580 line:15% 
for Network Plus is the TCP/IP model.

2
00:00:18,580 --> 00:00:23,580
This is also known as the TCP/IP stack or the DoD model.

3
00:00:23,840 --> 00:00:27,100
Now, this is an alternative to the OSI model,

4
00:00:27,100 --> 00:00:29,460
and the nice thing is, it's only four layers.

5
00:00:29,460 --> 00:00:30,690
So it's a little bit easier for

6
00:00:30,690 --> 00:00:33,170
most people to understand and learn.

7
00:00:33,170 --> 00:00:35,990
It is actually more relevant than the OSI model

8
00:00:35,990 --> 00:00:39,470
because today's networks are all TCP/IP based,

9
00:00:39,470 --> 00:00:43,310
and the TCP/IP model refers to it specifically

10
00:00:43,310 --> 00:00:45,770
in its four layers, where the OSI model,

11
00:00:45,770 --> 00:00:48,550
sometimes things get a little bit more blurred.

12
00:00:48,550 --> 00:00:52,830
So how does the OSI model compare to the TCP/IP model?

13
00:00:52,830 --> 00:00:54,990
Well, it's actually pretty simple.

14
00:00:54,990 --> 00:00:57,480
If I take layers five, six, and seven,

15
00:00:57,480 --> 00:01:00,350
the top three layers, and merge them all together,

16
00:01:00,350 --> 00:01:02,410
I get the application layer.

17
00:01:02,410 --> 00:01:05,200
So application, presentation, and session,

18
00:01:05,200 --> 00:01:08,110
all of those functions occur under application

19
00:01:08,110 --> 00:01:10,230
in the TCP/IP model.

20
00:01:10,230 --> 00:01:13,010
Transport gets carried right over.

21
00:01:13,010 --> 00:01:14,850
Network gets carried right over,

22
00:01:14,850 --> 00:01:17,180
but we call it Internet instead of network

23
00:01:17,180 --> 00:01:19,310
because it is really all about routing

24
00:01:19,310 --> 00:01:22,670
to external networks, or Internets.

25
00:01:22,670 --> 00:01:25,040
And then the final two is the bottom two layers,

26
00:01:25,040 --> 00:01:26,610
which is data link and physical,

27
00:01:26,610 --> 00:01:28,820
which is all about your internal network.

28
00:01:28,820 --> 00:01:31,540
And so we call that network interface,

29
00:01:31,540 --> 00:01:35,430
which is how you, the user, interfaces with the network.

30
00:01:35,430 --> 00:01:36,290
So that's how it is.

31
00:01:36,290 --> 00:01:38,700
It's pretty simple when you start looking at it that way.

32
00:01:38,700 --> 00:01:41,440
Take the top three, squish 'em together.

33
00:01:41,440 --> 00:01:43,930
Take the bottom two, squish them together.

34
00:01:43,930 --> 00:01:47,680
And that's how you get the four layers of your TCP/IP model.

35
00:01:47,680 --> 00:01:51,622
Now for the exam, you do need to understand the TCP/IP model

36
00:01:51,622 --> 00:01:54,210
and so, if you can draw this diagram,

37
00:01:54,210 --> 00:01:57,070
you're going to be covered there as you go through the test.

38
00:01:58,210 --> 00:02:00,770
The network interface layer, layer one,

39
00:02:00,770 --> 00:02:03,720
is all about physical and electrical characteristics,

40
00:02:03,720 --> 00:02:05,940
just like in the OSI model.

41
00:02:05,940 --> 00:02:07,790
It's going to describe how to transmit

42
00:02:07,790 --> 00:02:09,980
bits across the networks, those ones and zeros

43
00:02:09,980 --> 00:02:11,670
that we had in the physical layer,

44
00:02:11,670 --> 00:02:14,320
and it's going to determine how the network medium

45
00:02:14,320 --> 00:02:17,050
is going to be used, whether it's going to be coax,

46
00:02:17,050 --> 00:02:20,570
optical fiber, or twisted-pair copper cabling.

47
00:02:20,570 --> 00:02:22,240
This would be things like ethernet,

48
00:02:22,240 --> 00:02:27,240
token ring, fiber distribution networks, or RS-232.

49
00:02:27,360 --> 00:02:31,290
All of that gets put together inside of network interface.

50
00:02:31,290 --> 00:02:33,820
Now layer two here is the Internet layer.

51
00:02:33,820 --> 00:02:37,600
This is where we take data and package it into IP datagrams,

52
00:02:37,600 --> 00:02:40,110
like we did at layer three of the OSI model.

53
00:02:40,110 --> 00:02:43,020
It's going to contain your source and destination IPs and

54
00:02:43,020 --> 00:02:46,990
forward those datagrams between hosts across the network.

55
00:02:46,990 --> 00:02:49,370
These datagrams are going to be pushed around the networks

56
00:02:49,370 --> 00:02:51,390
through routing, and this connectivity

57
00:02:51,390 --> 00:02:53,160
is going to occur externally.

58
00:02:53,160 --> 00:02:57,340
This is where your Internet gets connected to your Internet,

59
00:02:57,340 --> 00:02:59,140
internal versus external.

60
00:02:59,140 --> 00:03:02,980
Examples of this are going to be IP, ICMP,

61
00:03:02,980 --> 00:03:05,030
ARP, and reverse ARP.

62
00:03:05,030 --> 00:03:06,520
And we will talk about all of those

63
00:03:06,520 --> 00:03:08,440
as we go through switching and routing

64
00:03:08,440 --> 00:03:10,190
in the next section of this course.

65
00:03:11,400 --> 00:03:13,880
Layer three here is going to be the transport layer,

66
00:03:13,880 --> 00:03:17,430
and it's exactly the same as transport in OSI.

67
00:03:17,430 --> 00:03:19,440
It gives you communication session management

68
00:03:19,440 --> 00:03:22,430
between hosts, and it's going to define the level of service

69
00:03:22,430 --> 00:03:24,210
and the status of the connection used

70
00:03:24,210 --> 00:03:28,820
using TCP, UDP or RTP, the real-time protocol,

71
00:03:28,820 --> 00:03:30,710
which is used for voice and video.

72
00:03:32,270 --> 00:03:34,630
Application, or layer four, is going to combine

73
00:03:34,630 --> 00:03:36,820
the top three layers of the OSI model,

74
00:03:36,820 --> 00:03:40,240
and it's going to define the application protocols being used.

75
00:03:40,240 --> 00:03:42,360
It's going to tell you how the programs are going to interface

76
00:03:42,360 --> 00:03:45,290
with the transport layer, and it's going to be the layer

77
00:03:45,290 --> 00:03:47,920
where the user is going to interact with.

78
00:03:47,920 --> 00:03:51,940
Now, examples of this come from layers five, six, and seven

79
00:03:51,940 --> 00:03:53,530
of the OSI model again, right,

80
00:03:53,530 --> 00:03:55,190
because we squished those down.

81
00:03:55,190 --> 00:03:57,870
This would be things like hypertext transfer protocol

82
00:03:57,870 --> 00:04:01,530
for web browsing, TELNET for remote control,

83
00:04:01,530 --> 00:04:05,170
FTP, or file transfer protocol, for file-sharing,

84
00:04:05,170 --> 00:04:07,272
SNMP for network management,

85
00:04:07,272 --> 00:04:10,510
DNS for domain name resolution,

86
00:04:10,510 --> 00:04:12,960
SMTP for sending mail,

87
00:04:12,960 --> 00:04:17,550
SSL and TLS for secure web browsing and encryption.

88
00:04:17,550 --> 00:04:19,660
All of these things are going to be found here

89
00:04:19,660 --> 00:04:21,990
in layer four, the application layer.
